abstract: FULTON, N.Y., Sept. 1. -- Train No. 5 on the New York, Ontario and Western Railroad, known as the "Chicago Limited," was wrecked at Ingell's Crossing, four miles south of this village, at 5 o'clock this morning. abstract: EASTHAMPTON, L.I., Sept. 1. -- The residents of Easthampton are bestirring themselves to relieve the sufferings at Camp Wikoff. This regiment was organized principally in Westchester, Putnam, and Rockland Counties, and was mustered in at Yonkers, Sept. 2, 1862. It saw service in thirty-six engagements and returned with but 700 men out of the total of 2,400 which were entered upon its rolls during the term of service.

abstract: LITTLE, ROCK, Ark., Sept. 3. -- The State campaign closed to-night, and the election will occur on Monday. abstract: So Gen. Miles is going to "fight" the Secretary of War! He does not seem to read history -- even modern history! The Secretary of War is simply the clerk of the President, and, presumably, carries out the orders of the Commander in Chief of the Army.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Sept. 6. -- Some changes in the Cuban and Puerto Rican tariff rates were approved by the President to-day, and cabled to the United States officers in those places. Another change was in the administrative features of the Cuban tariff.

abstract: A historic landmark, the old three-story frame building at Fulton and Water Streets, which for ninety years was known as Brown's Drug Store, was burned early yesterday morning. abstract: The habit of birds in regard to sleep are very unlike, some being extremely solicitous to be in bed in good time, while others are awake and about all night. abstract: NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J., Sept. 11. -- Mrs. Caroline Gerlach, thirty-five years old, of Milltown, was burned to death this morning at her home. She was engaged in starting the fire, and because it did not burn to suit her she used kerosene. The blaze communicated to the oil in the can and the can exploded. Mrs. Gerlach was almost instantly enveloped in flame from head to foot.

abstract: NEWARK, N.J., Sept. 11. -- The members of the First Regiment, New Jersey Volunteers, over 900 in number, who have been in town on an eight days' furlough, returned to Sea Girt this afternoon. The men left from the Central Railroad station, Broad Street, at 5 P.M. Several thousand persons saw them off, and there was nearly as much weeping and cheering as there was when they left home four months ago.

abstract: BERNE, Switzerland, Sept. 11. -- Emperor Francis Joseph telegraphed the Austrian Minister, Count von Kuefstein, to consent to a post-mortem examination. Dr. Reverdin, Dr. Megedaus, and M. abstract: WASHINGTON, Sept. 14. -- A further extension of the postal service in Puerto Rico has been made, the following towns having been designated as postal stations: Coamo, Utuamo, Yacuo, and Juandiaz. In many cases the Spanish officials are permitted to administer the duties in such offices, but are under the supervision of American authorities.

abstract: SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico, Sept. 15. -- The work of the United States Evacuation Commission is proceeding rapidly. Two sessions were held yesterday. There has been no hitch yet. Both sides profess satisfaction, and by mutual agreement no details of the deliberations are made public. The report circulated here that the American Commissioners have agreed to pay $7,000,000 for the Spanish fortifications and other property is preposterous.

abstract: Nature, not being a European power, keeps her forces in readiness where they are needed, in consequence of which the scavengers muster in strength in hot countries. abstract: The common expression "tailor-made" has come, after much use, to have no meaning. Any sort of a gown, simply made of cloth with stitched seams, is known as a tailor-made gown, and much the wearer thereof has plumed herself upon it; but she must lower her pinions. If the tailor-made girl is not wearing a "man-tailored" suit she is not a tailor-made girl at all, but a fraud who is not what she seems.

abstract: One may obtain a fairly complete collection of postage stamps, but never of insects. Some experts say that there are 100,000 species of insects in the United States, while others put the estimate much higher. abstract: SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico, Sept. 19. -- The evacuation of the outlying positions occupied by the Spaniards began to-day. Aguadilla, San Sebastian, and Lares were abandoned by them and the troops of Gen. Garniton's brigade and the Eleventh Infantry moved in and noisted the American flag. The Spanish troops from the abandoned positions are being concentrated at Arecibo, whence they will reach San Juan by railroad so soon as transportation is available.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Sept. 21. -- A dispatch was received at the War Department this evening from Col. Kimball, Depot Quartermaster in New York, announcing the sailing of the transport Berlin for Santiago. abstract: The Homeric women generally are characterized by a gentle dignity and a refinement in which no modern civilization could show their superiors. abstract: In parts of Central America little visited by civilized man remnants of once powerful tribes, now feeble and almost extinct, are occasionally discovered. abstract: TRENTON, N.J., Sept. 27. -- A meeting was held in Taylor's Opera House this afternoon by two dozen colored men, some of them Democrats and others dissatisfied Republicans, representing seventeen counties. The resolutions pledge support to the nominee, for Governor, of to-morrow's Democratic Convention.

abstract: KINGSTOWN, St. Vincent, Sept. 16. -- A terrible storm passed over this island last Sunday, with the result that scarcely a building is left standing throughout the country, while about half of this place is destroyed. abstract: An English observer now in Havana asserts that of all the harm done by what he, somewhat inaccurately, calls "this prolonged civil war," the most terrible and irremediable has been the havoc wrought among the white population. abstract: Harry Watson, twenty-five years old, a private of Company D, Fourteenth Regiment New York Volunteers, was removed yesterday, together with his wife, from their home at 326 Twelfth Street, Brooklyn, to the Long Island College Hospital, Brooklyn.
